.TH _PRINTF 3 "24 Feb 2026" "1.0" "holberton printf function"
.SH NAME
_printf \- produces output according to a format string
.SH SYNOPSIS
#include "main.h"

int _printf(const char *format, ...);
.SH DESCRIPTION
The \f_printf\fP function writes output to the standard output (stdout) according to the format specified in the \f=format\fP string. 

The format string may contain plain characters, which are written as-is, and conversion specifiers, introduced by the percent character '%' to indicate that an argument should be formatted and inserted.

Supported conversion specifiers:

.TP
\fB%c\fR
Prints a single character. The corresponding argument must be an int.

.TP
\fB%s\fR
Prints a string. The corresponding argument must be a char *. If the argument is NULL, "(null)" is printed.

.TP
\fB%%\fR
Prints a literal '%' character. No argument is consumed.

.TP
\fB%d\fR, \fBi\fR
Prints a signed decimal integer. The corresponding argument must be an int.

.SH RETURN VALUE
On success, \f_printf\fP returns the number of characters printed (excluding the null byte used internally). 

If the format string is NULL, or a '%' is followed by a null byte, \f_printf\fP returns -1.

.SH ERRORS
If a conversion specifier is not recognized, the '%' and the unknown specifier are printed literally.

.SH EXAMPLES
The following example prints a string and a character:

.EX
_printf("Hello %s%c\n", "World", '!');
.END

This prints:
Hello World!

The following example prints a percent sign:
.EX
_printf("100%% complete\n");
.END

.SH NOTES
This function does not handle:
.RS
- Flag characters
- Field width
- Precision
- Length modifiers
.RE
It is a simplified version of the standard \fCprintf\fR function.

.SH SEE ALSO
printf(3), write(2), va_start(3), va_end(3), va_arg(3)
